notes: Many figures of this dance end with a rigaudon, which involves doing footwork in place. I have substituted arm movements or balances so that these are visible. In the 'calls' displayed below, I have used modern terminology such as 'heads' and 'sides' for the opposite pairs of couples, and 'larks' and 'robins' in place of 'gents' and 'ladies' (or 'cavaliers' and 'dames').

sequence.call: Heads advance while sides go out to corners, then rigaudon
Head larks take opposite robin home while sides return to place
Sides advance while heads go out to corners, then rigaudon
Side larks take opposite robin home while heads return to place
Form a double moulinet, then rigaudon
Robins turn their moulinet halfway, then courtesy turn with their partner
Robins form a moulinet again with larks connected to their partner and the robin to their left, then rigaudon
